Note:
COBOL Semantic Analyzer - structure and reference analysis over the parser AST.

This pass walks the binary AST produced by cobol_parser.runa and performs real
two-phase COBOL-85 semantic analysis:

Phase 1 (collection) records every data-item name declared in the DATA DIVISION
and every paragraph / section name declared in the PROCEDURE DIVISION, so that a
PERFORM or GO TO that targets a paragraph defined later in the program still
resolves, and so a MOVE / COMPUTE can be checked against the full data dictionary
regardless of definition order.

Phase 2 (validation) walks the program checking real COBOL conditions:
- IDENTIFICATION DIVISION must be present and must carry a PROGRAM-ID.
- PROCEDURE DIVISION must be present.
- Every data item's level number must be a legal COBOL level (01-49 for the
  regular hierarchy, or 66 / 77 / 88 for the special forms).
- Every data item's PICTURE clause, when present, must be well formed (no mixed
  numeric/alphabetic classes, S only in the leading position, at most one implied
  decimal point, and only valid PICTURE symbols).
- Every PERFORM and GO TO target paragraph must exist in the procedure name set.
- Every MOVE source / target and every COMPUTE target identifier must resolve to
  a declared data item.

The AST is read entirely through the contract documented in cobol_parser.runa: a
node is a 48-byte record [type @0][name @8][value @16][children @24]
[child_count @32][metadata @40]; node type is an integer COBOL_* constant; the
name / value slots hold StringCore lexeme handles; children is a flat array of
node pointers; keyed attributes ("level", "picture", "operator", ...) are read
with get_node_attribute. Diagnostics accumulate as message strings on the
analyzer's error and warning lists rather than aborting the walk, so a single
malformed construct never suppresses reporting on the rest of the program.

Dependencies:
- compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/cobol/cobol_parser.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/cobol/cobol_parser.runa" as CobolParser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListOps
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ANALYZER STATE
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The analyzer threads four flat string-handle lists through the two-phase walk:
data_names (every data item declared in the DATA DIVISION), procedure_names
(every paragraph and section declared in the PROCEDURE DIVISION), errors, and
warnings. COBOL has no block scope for data names — WORKING-STORAGE / FILE /
LINKAGE items and all paragraph labels share one program-wide namespace — so flat
definition sets exactly model COBOL visibility and keep reference resolution a
single linear membership test.
@End Reasoning
Type called "CobolSemanticAnalyzer":
    data_names as Integer        Note: List of declared data-item name handles
    procedure_names as Integer   Note: List of declared paragraph/section name handles
    errors as Integer            Note: List of error message strings
    warnings as Integer          Note: List of warning message strings
End Type

@Reasoning:
Allocates a 32-byte analyzer with four freshly-created lists so each analysis run
starts with empty definition and diagnostic state. Returns 0 on allocation
failure so callers can guard.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_cobol_semantic_analyzer" returns Integer:
    Note: Create a fresh COBOL semantic analyzer

    Let analyzer be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let data_names be proc create from ListOps
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0, data_names

    Let procedure_names be proc create from ListOps
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8, procedure_names

    Let errors be proc create from ListOps
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16, errors

    Let warnings be proc create from ListOps
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24, warnings

    Return analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Releases the analyzer struct. The four lists are borrowed by callers that may read
diagnostics afterward, so only the 32-byte struct is freed here; callers own the
analysis lifetime.
@End Reasoning
Process called "destroy_cobol_semantic_analyzer" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    proc deallocate from Layout with analyzer
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: NODE ACCESSORS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Reads a node's integer type constant from offset 0; null-guards the node so a
missing child never dereferences a null pointer.
@End Reasoning
Process called "node_type_of" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reads a node's name lexeme handle from offset 8 (the identifier for paragraphs,
sections, data items, PROGRAM-ID, and PERFORM targets).
@End Reasoning
Process called "node_name" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reads a node's children array pointer from offset 24.
@End Reasoning
Process called "node_children" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 24
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reads a node's child count from offset 32.
@End Reasoning
Process called "node_child_count" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the i-th child node pointer, or 0 when the index is out of range or the
node has no children array. Children are stored as a flat int64 array, so element
i lives at byte offset i * 8.
@End Reasoning
Process called "node_child" takes node as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Let children be proc node_children with node
    If children is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc node_child_count with node
    If index is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If index is greater than or equal to count:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let offset be index multiplied by 8
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, offset
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reads a keyed node attribute ("level", "picture", "operator", ...) through the
parser's metadata accessor, returning 0 when absent.
@End Reasoning
Process called "node_attr" takes node as Integer, key as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc get_node_attribute from CobolParser with node, key
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DIAGNOSTICS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Records a semantic error message on the analyzer's error list. Messages are plain
strings so the downstream driver can present them without knowing the analyzer's
internal layout.
@End Reasoning
Process called "add_semantic_error" takes analyzer as Integer, message as Integer returns Integer:
    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let errors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16
    proc list_append from ListOps with errors, message
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Records a semantic warning message on the analyzer's warning list.
@End Reasoning
Process called "add_semantic_warning" takes analyzer as Integer, message as Integer returns Integer:
    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24
    proc list_append from ListOps with warnings, message
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the accumulated error list for the driver.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_semantic_errors" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the accumulated warning list for the driver.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_semantic_warnings" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: NAME TABLES
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Records a declared data-item name into the program-wide data dictionary so a
later MOVE / COMPUTE reference resolves regardless of definition order. A null or
empty handle is ignored; duplicate names are tolerated because COBOL permits
qualified duplicates (the resolver only needs membership, not uniqueness).
@End Reasoning
Process called "define_data_name" takes analyzer as Integer, name as Integer returns Integer:
    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If name is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let names be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    proc list_append from ListOps with names, name
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Records a declared paragraph or section name into the procedure name set so a
PERFORM / GO TO that targets it resolves regardless of definition order.
@End Reasoning
Process called "define_procedure_name" takes analyzer as Integer, name as Integer returns Integer:
    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If name is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let names be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    proc list_append from ListOps with names, name
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
True (1) when a data-item name is present in the program-wide data dictionary.
Linear scan comparing each declared name with string_equals. COBOL's figurative
constants (ZERO, SPACE(S), HIGH-VALUE(S), LOW-VALUE(S), QUOTE(S), ALL) are
always-available literals, so a reference to one resolves without an explicit
declaration.
@End Reasoning
Process called "data_name_defined" takes analyzer as Integer, name as Integer returns Integer:
    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If name is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If proc is_figurative_constant with name is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let names be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    Let count be proc list_length from ListOps with names
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let dn be proc list_get from ListOps with names, i
        Let matches be proc string_equals from StringCore with dn, name
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
True (1) when a paragraph / section name is present in the procedure name set.
Linear membership test mirroring data_name_defined.
@End Reasoning
Process called "procedure_name_defined" takes analyzer as Integer, name as Integer returns Integer:
    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If name is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let names be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let count be proc list_length from ListOps with names
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let pn be proc list_get from ListOps with names, i
        Let matches be proc string_equals from StringCore with pn, name
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
True (1) when a name is one of COBOL's figurative constants. These denote
implicit literal values (all-zeros, all-spaces, the highest/lowest collating
value, the quote character) and are valid operands anywhere a data item may
appear, so the resolver must never flag them as undefined. Singular and plural
spellings are listed separately because COBOL accepts both forms as distinct
spellings of the same value.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_figurative_constant" takes name as Integer returns Integer:
    If name is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with name, "ZERO" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with name, "ZEROS" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with name, "ZEROES" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with name, "SPACE" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with name, "SPACES" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with name, "HIGH-VALUE" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with name, "HIGH-VALUES" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with name, "LOW-VALUE" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with name, "LOW-VALUES" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with name, "QUOTE" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with name, "QUOTES" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with name, "ALL" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: NUMERIC LEXEME PARSING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A data item's level number reaches the analyzer as the raw lexeme handle the
lexer captured (e.g. the two bytes "01"), not as a parsed integer, because the
parser stores it verbatim under the "level" attribute. Validation needs the
numeric value, so this converts the leading run of ASCII digits in a
NUL-terminated lexeme to an integer. A handle of 0 or a lexeme with no leading
digit yields -1 so the caller can distinguish "absent / malformed" from any legal
level. Bytes are read with string_char_at; ASCII '0'..'9' are codes 48..57.
@End Reasoning
Process called "lexeme_to_int" takes lexeme as Integer returns Integer:
    If lexeme is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If

    Let first be proc string_char_at from StringCore with lexeme, 0
    If first is less than 48:
        Return -1
    End If
    If first is greater than 57:
        Return -1
    End If

    Let value be 0
    Let index be 0
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with lexeme, index
        If ch is less than 48:
            Return value
        End If
        If ch is greater than 57:
            Return value
        End If
        Let digit be ch minus 48
        Set value to value multiplied by 10
        Set value to value plus digit
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return value
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TOP-LEVEL ANALYSIS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Entry point. Performs a two-phase analysis over the COBOL_PROGRAM root and its
division children. Phase 1 collects every data-item and procedure name so forward
references (a PERFORM of a paragraph defined later, a MOVE into a field declared
after the procedure body) resolve. Phase 2 validates division presence and then
walks every division checking the structural and reference conditions. A null AST
is a no-op success so the driver can call unconditionally.
@End Reasoning
@Security_Scope:
The input AST is untrusted; every validator records diagnostics via
add_semantic_error / add_semantic_warning and returns rather than aborting, so a
malformed subtree cannot prevent analysis of its siblings.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "analyze_cobol_ast" takes analyzer as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Two-phase semantic analysis of a parsed COBOL program

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Phase 1 - collect data-item and procedure names for forward references
    proc collect_definitions with analyzer, ast

    Note: Phase 2 - validate program structure and resolve references
    proc validate_program with analyzer, ast

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PHASE 1 - DEFINITION COLLECTION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Walks the program root's division children. DATA DIVISION contributes data-item
names; PROCEDURE DIVISION contributes paragraph and section names. Other
divisions declare no referenceable names. Recursing per-division keeps the
collector aligned with COBOL's structure rather than blindly flattening the tree.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_definitions" takes analyzer as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let count be proc node_child_count with ast
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc node_child with ast, i
        Let child_type be proc node_type_of with child

        If child_type is equal to COBOL_DATA_DIV from CobolParser:
            proc collect_data_names with analyzer, child
        End If
        If child_type is equal to COBOL_PROCEDURE_DIV from CobolParser:
            proc collect_procedure_names with analyzer, child
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recursively gathers every COBOL_DATA_ITEM name beneath the DATA DIVISION. Data
items nest (group items contain elementary items as children, and sections wrap
items), so the walk descends through every node and records the name of each
data-item node it meets. Non-item nodes (sections, file descriptions) contribute
no name but are still descended into to reach the items they contain.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_data_names" takes analyzer as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let nt be proc node_type_of with node
    If nt is equal to COBOL_DATA_ITEM from CobolParser:
        Let name be proc node_name with node
        If name is not equal to 0:
            proc define_data_name with analyzer, name
        End If
    End If

    Let count be proc node_child_count with node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc node_child with node, i
        proc collect_data_names with analyzer, child
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recursively gathers every paragraph and section label beneath the PROCEDURE
DIVISION. A section node contains paragraph children, so recording both the
section's own name and descending into it captures the full set of PERFORM / GO TO
targets.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_procedure_names" takes analyzer as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let nt be proc node_type_of with node
    If nt is equal to COBOL_PARAGRAPH from CobolParser:
        Let pname be proc node_name with node
        If pname is not equal to 0:
            proc define_procedure_name with analyzer, pname
        End If
    End If
    If nt is equal to COBOL_SECTION from CobolParser:
        Let sname be proc node_name with node
        If sname is not equal to 0:
            proc define_procedure_name with analyzer, sname
        End If
    End If

    Let count be proc node_child_count with node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc node_child with node, i
        proc collect_procedure_names with analyzer, child
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PHASE 2 - VALIDATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
COBOL-85 mandates IDENTIFICATION DIVISION (carrying a PROGRAM-ID) and PROCEDURE
DIVISION; ENVIRONMENT and DATA are optional. A single scan over the division
children records which mandatory divisions are present and validates the
IDENTIFICATION division's PROGRAM-ID, then descends into DATA (level/PICTURE
checks) and PROCEDURE (reference checks). Missing mandatory divisions are reported
individually so the user sees each omission.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_program" takes analyzer as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let has_identification be 0
    Let has_procedure be 0

    Let count be proc node_child_count with ast
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc node_child with ast, i
        Let child_type be proc node_type_of with child

        If child_type is equal to COBOL_IDENTIFICATION_DIV from CobolParser:
            Set has_identification to 1
            proc validate_identification_division with analyzer, child
        End If
        If child_type is equal to COBOL_DATA_DIV from CobolParser:
            proc validate_data_division with analyzer, child
        End If
        If child_type is equal to COBOL_PROCEDURE_DIV from CobolParser:
            Set has_procedure to 1
            proc validate_procedure_division with analyzer, child
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If has_identification is equal to 0:
        proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Missing IDENTIFICATION DIVISION"
    End If
    If has_procedure is equal to 0:
        proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Missing PROCEDURE DIVISION"
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
The parser stores PROGRAM-ID under the IDENTIFICATION division node's name slot.
COBOL-85 requires PROGRAM-ID, so a division with no name handle is a structural
error. This is the one IDENTIFICATION-division check with semantic weight; the
optional AUTHOR / DATE-WRITTEN paragraphs are documentation and carry no
constraint.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_identification_division" takes analyzer as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let program_id be proc node_name with node
    If program_id is equal to 0:
        proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "IDENTIFICATION DIVISION missing PROGRAM-ID"
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Descends the DATA DIVISION validating every data item it contains. The recursion
mirrors the collector: every COBOL_DATA_ITEM is validated (level number then
PICTURE) and every node is descended into so nested group / section structure is
reached.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_data_division" takes analyzer as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let nt be proc node_type_of with node
    If nt is equal to COBOL_DATA_ITEM from CobolParser:
        proc validate_data_item with analyzer, node
    End If

    Let count be proc node_child_count with node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc node_child with node, i
        proc validate_data_division with analyzer, child
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
A data item carries a level number (mandatory) and an optional PICTURE clause.
The level number must be a legal COBOL level: 01-49 for the regular hierarchy, or
the special independent / renaming / condition forms 66, 77, 88. lexeme_to_int
returns -1 for a missing or non-numeric level, which is itself an error. When a
PICTURE is present it is validated for class consistency and symbol legality.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_data_item" takes analyzer as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let level_lexeme be proc node_attr with node, "level"
    Let level be proc lexeme_to_int with level_lexeme

    If level is less than 1:
        proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Data item missing or non-numeric level number"
    Otherwise:
        If level is greater than 49:
            If level is not equal to 66:
                If level is not equal to 77:
                    If level is not equal to 88:
                        proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Invalid COBOL level number (must be 01-49, 66, 77, or 88)"
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Let picture be proc node_attr with node, "picture"
    If picture is not equal to 0:
        proc validate_picture_clause with analyzer, picture
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
COBOL PICTURE syntax has hard invariants enforced here by a single linear pass
over the symbol bytes (a PICTURE string is short and NUL-terminated): the sign
symbol S may appear only as the first character; the implied-decimal symbol V may
appear at most once; numeric symbols (9) may not be combined with alphabetic
symbols (A); and only recognised PICTURE symbols may appear. Each violation is
reported against the offending property so the user sees the precise fault rather
than a generic rejection. An empty PICTURE handle (a present but zero-length
clause) is itself invalid.
@End Reasoning
@Performance_Hints:
PICTURE strings are short (typically under 16 symbols); a single byte scan with
running class flags is optimal and avoids any allocation.
@End Performance_Hints
Process called "validate_picture_clause" takes analyzer as Integer, picture as Integer returns Integer:
    If picture is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let pic_length be proc string_length from StringCore with picture
    If pic_length is equal to 0:
        proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Empty PICTURE clause"
        Return 1
    End If

    Let has_numeric be 0
    Let has_alpha be 0
    Let decimal_count be 0
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than pic_length:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with picture, index

        If ch is equal to 57:
            Note: '9' numeric digit position
            Set has_numeric to 1
        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 88:
                Note: 'X' alphanumeric position
                Set has_alpha to 1
            Otherwise:
                If ch is equal to 65:
                    Note: 'A' alphabetic position
                    Set has_alpha to 1
                Otherwise:
                    If ch is equal to 86:
                        Note: 'V' implied decimal point
                        Set decimal_count to decimal_count plus 1
                    Otherwise:
                        If ch is equal to 83:
                            Note: 'S' operational sign - legal only first
                            If index is not equal to 0:
                                proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "PICTURE sign S must be the first symbol"
                            End If
                        Otherwise:
                            If proc is_valid_picture_symbol with ch is equal to 0:
                                proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Invalid symbol in PICTURE clause"
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    If decimal_count is greater than 1:
        proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "PICTURE clause has more than one implied decimal point (V)"
    End If

    If has_numeric is equal to 1:
        If has_alpha is equal to 1:
            proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "PICTURE clause mixes numeric and alphabetic classes"
        End If
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recognises the remaining legal COBOL PICTURE symbols beyond the class symbols
(9 / X / A), the sign (S), and the implied decimal (V) handled directly by the
caller: editing and structural symbols P (decimal scaling), Z (zero suppression),
the actual decimal point (.), the parenthesised repeat-count delimiters ( and ),
the digits 0-9 that form a repeat count, the insertion characters comma, slash,
space (B), and the currency / sign editing symbols $ + - * and CR/DB initials
C D R. Anything else is rejected by the caller. Comparisons are on ASCII byte
codes so no per-character string allocation is needed.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_valid_picture_symbol" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: P
    If ch is equal to 80:
        Return 1
    End If
    Note: Z
    If ch is equal to 90:
        Return 1
    End If
    Note: B (blank insertion)
    If ch is equal to 66:
        Return 1
    End If
    Note: . decimal point
    If ch is equal to 46:
        Return 1
    End If
    Note: , comma insertion
    If ch is equal to 44:
        Return 1
    End If
    Note: / slash insertion
    If ch is equal to 47:
        Return 1
    End If
    Note: ( open repeat count
    If ch is equal to 40:
        Return 1
    End If
    Note: ) close repeat count
    If ch is equal to 41:
        Return 1
    End If
    Note: $ currency
    If ch is equal to 36:
        Return 1
    End If
    Note: + plus sign editing
    If ch is equal to 43:
        Return 1
    End If
    Note: - minus sign editing
    If ch is equal to 45:
        Return 1
    End If
    Note: * check-protect
    If ch is equal to 42:
        Return 1
    End If
    Note: C (CR credit symbol)
    If ch is equal to 67:
        Return 1
    End If
    Note: D (DB debit symbol)
    If ch is equal to 68:
        Return 1
    End If
    Note: R (second letter of CR)
    If ch is equal to 82:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Digits 0-9 forming repeat counts inside parentheses
    If ch is greater than or equal to 48:
        If ch is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PROCEDURE DIVISION VALIDATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Walks the PROCEDURE DIVISION recursively dispatching each statement to its
reference validator. PERFORM and GO TO targets must be declared paragraphs; MOVE
and COMPUTE operands must be declared data items (or figurative constants). Every
other node is descended into so statements nested inside paragraphs, sections,
IF / ELSE bodies, and EVALUATE WHEN clauses are all reached.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_procedure_division" takes analyzer as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let nt be proc node_type_of with node

    If nt is equal to COBOL_PERFORM_STMT from CobolParser:
        proc validate_perform with analyzer, node
    End If
    If nt is equal to COBOL_GO_STMT from CobolParser:
        proc validate_go_to with analyzer, node
    End If
    If nt is equal to COBOL_MOVE_STMT from CobolParser:
        proc validate_move with analyzer, node
    End If
    If nt is equal to COBOL_COMPUTE_STMT from CobolParser:
        proc validate_compute with analyzer, node
    End If

    Let count be proc node_child_count with node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc node_child with node, i
        proc validate_procedure_division with analyzer, child
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
A PERFORM that names a target paragraph stores that name in the node's name slot
(the conditional PERFORM UNTIL / VARYING forms carry a condition child instead and
no name). When a name is present it must resolve to a declared paragraph or
section; an unresolved target is a genuine control-flow error because the runtime
would have nowhere to transfer to.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_perform" takes analyzer as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let target be proc node_name with node
    If target is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    If proc procedure_name_defined with analyzer, target is equal to 0:
        proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "PERFORM targets undefined paragraph"
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
GO TO transfers control to a paragraph; its target is parsed into an identifier
child. The first identifier child names the destination paragraph, which must
exist in the procedure name set.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_go_to" takes analyzer as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let target be proc node_name with node
    If target is equal to 0:
        Note: The parser may attach the destination as the first identifier child
        Note: rather than the name slot; resolve it from there when present.
        Let first_child be proc node_child with node, 0
        If first_child is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If
        Let child_type be proc node_type_of with first_child
        If child_type is not equal to COBOL_IDENTIFIER from CobolParser:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set target to proc node_name with first_child
        If target is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If proc procedure_name_defined with analyzer, target is equal to 0:
        proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "GO TO targets undefined paragraph"
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
MOVE stores its source as the first child and each destination as a subsequent
child, all parsed as COBOL_IDENTIFIER (or literal / figurative) expression nodes.
Every identifier operand must resolve to a declared data item; literals and
figurative constants carry their value in the value slot (no name) and need no
declaration, so only name-bearing identifier children are checked.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_move" takes analyzer as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count be proc node_child_count with node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let operand be proc node_child with node, i
        proc validate_identifier_reference with analyzer, operand
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
COMPUTE stores its result variable as the first child and the arithmetic
expression tree as the second. The result identifier must resolve to a declared
data item; the expression is walked recursively so every identifier leaf inside
it is also checked. Validating the whole subtree catches references in deeply
nested arithmetic, not just the top-level result.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_compute" takes analyzer as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count be proc node_child_count with node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc node_child with node, i
        proc validate_expression_references with analyzer, child
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recursively checks every identifier leaf in an arithmetic expression subtree. A
COBOL_IDENTIFIER must resolve to a declared data item; a COBOL_ARITHMETIC_EXPR
holds operand children that are recursed into; literals terminate the recursion
because every literal is a valid operand. This lets COMPUTE validation cover the
entire right-hand side rather than only its root.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_expression_references" takes analyzer as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let nt be proc node_type_of with node
    If nt is equal to COBOL_IDENTIFIER from CobolParser:
        proc validate_identifier_reference with analyzer, node
        Return 1
    End If

    Let count be proc node_child_count with node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc node_child with node, i
        proc validate_expression_references with analyzer, child
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Checks a single operand node: only COBOL_IDENTIFIER nodes name data items that
must be declared. Literal and figurative-constant nodes carry no name slot (their
content is in the value slot) and require no declaration, so they pass silently.
An identifier whose name does not resolve to a declared data item or figurative
constant is reported as an undefined-reference error.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_identifier_reference" takes analyzer as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let nt be proc node_type_of with node
    If nt is not equal to COBOL_IDENTIFIER from CobolParser:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let name be proc node_name with node
    If name is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    If proc data_name_defined with analyzer, name is equal to 0:
        proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Reference to undefined data item"
    End If

    Return 1
End Process
